{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"46f89a8f-0f79-4ff5-b479-460b31351c75","content":"Here's the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test \\\n  -- \\\n  --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage \\\n  --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump \\\n  --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|--------|---------------------------|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\nOptions after `--` are forwarded to the platform runner.\n\n**Required packages** in your test project:\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\nAnd ensure your project has:\n```xml\n<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3feacc4a-5ed4-4be8-a94e-8a48faa73b8e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. Let me provide the equivalent command.\n\nKey differences with Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n- `--filter` becomes `--filter`  (same, but uses `--treenode-filter` for the new filter syntax, though `--filter` is still supported for compatibility)\n- `--logger trx` becomes `--report-trx`\n- `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` becomes `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura`\n- `--blame-crash` becomes `--crashdump`\n\n\n- `--blame-hang` and `--blame-hang-timeout 5m` becomes `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m`\n\nWith Microsoft.Testing.Platform, you can still use `dotnet test`, though the arguments change—anything after `--` gets passed to the platform, and if your project is configured for it, `dotnet test` will automatically use the new platform.\n\nFor .NET 8, you typically need to enable `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in your project file, or just run the test executable directly. Let me work through what the equivalent command would look like with the new platform flags. Each of those extensions needs to be installed as a NuGet package, and then you can use their corresponding flags in the command. When running directly through `dotnet run`, you pass all the options after `--`, or if you're using `dotnet test` with the platform integration enabled, the syntax is slightly different but the flags remain the same.","outputTokens":1367,"requestId":"6815:334824:751122:7C7D5B:6A044DA8"},"id":"5cf2d958-ebaf-4d64-b817-072df9851059","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:09:07.091Z","parentId":"f49245a0-b682-4e15-998e-fd37a8e8c834"}
